    abstract = {Two chiral œÄ‚Äêconjugated polymers with optical nonlinearity (NLO), abbreviated as R‚Äê and S‚ÄêBP , are prepared by copolymerization of R‚Äê and S‚Äê6,6'‚Äêdibromo‚Äê2,2'‚Äêdiethoxy‚Äê1,1'‚Äêbinaphthyl with 1,4‚Äêdiethynyl‚Äê2,5‚Äêbis(octyloxy)benzene by Sonogashira coupling. The R‚Äê and S‚ÄêBP copolymers self‚Äêassemble in a tetrahydrofuran/H2O/ethanol mixture producing microspherical particles. Remarkably, the obtained polymer microspheres support excitation of whispering gallery mode resonances (500‚Äì720 nm) in one‚Äê and two‚Äêphoton excited luminescence or two‚Äêphoton luminescence (TPL) with a quality factor (Q ) of up to ‚âà700. As a result of a high Q value, a single (R‚Äê or S‚ÄêBP ) microsphere displays a circular dichroism (CD) effect in the TPL signal. At high laser pump‚Äêpower (‚â•10 mW), the TPL spectral features of microspheres change significantly, suggesting alterations of the polymer packing. Similar spectral variations are observed for microspheres heated thermally or with high power continuous‚Äêwave laser. Photoluminescence lifetime imaging microscopy down to the single microsphere level corroborate transformations of polymer packing from a J type to a mixture of J , H , and H‚Äêlike (with disordered side chains) types. This work demonstrates the tremendous potential of tailor‚Äêmade chiral polymer microspheres exhibiting multifunctional properties, such as i) light‚Äêconfinement, ii) NLO‚ÄêCD, and iii) laser‚Äêdriven optical emission shifts, useful for many optoelectronic and photonic device applications.},
